**Smart Pointers in C++: `std::shared_ptr` vs `std::unique_ptr`**
===========================================================

C++ provides two smart pointer classes, `std::shared_ptr` and `std::unique_ptr`, to manage dynamic memory allocation. While both classes aim to prevent memory leaks, they differ in their ownership semantics and usage scenarios.

**`std::unique_ptr`**
--------------------

`std::unique_ptr` is a smart pointer that owns and manages another object through a pointer. It provides exclusive ownership, meaning that only one `std::unique_ptr` can point to a particular object at a time. When a `std::unique_ptr` is destroyed, the object it points to is also destroyed.

**Key characteristics:**

* Exclusive ownership
* Cannot be copied, only moved
* Automatically deletes the managed object when it goes out of scope

**Example use case:**
```cpp
#include <memory>

class MyClass {
public:
    MyClass() { std::cout << "MyClass constructed\n"; }
    ~MyClass() { std::cout << "MyClass destroyed\n"; }
};

int main() {
    std::unique_ptr<MyClass> ptr(new MyClass());
    // ptr is the sole owner of the MyClass object
    // When ptr goes out of scope, the MyClass object is destroyed
    return 0;
}
```
**`std::shared_ptr`**
--------------------

`std::shared_ptr` is a smart pointer that retains shared ownership of an object through a pointer. Multiple `std::shared_ptr` instances can point to the same object, and the object is destroyed when the last `std::shared_ptr` pointing to it is destroyed.

**Key characteristics:**

* Shared ownership
* Can be copied and moved
* Automatically deletes the managed object when the last `std::shared_ptr` is destroyed

**Example use case:**
```cpp
#include <memory>

class MyClass {
public:
    MyClass() { std::cout << "MyClass constructed\n"; }
    ~MyClass() { std::cout << "MyClass destroyed\n"; }
};

int main() {
    std::shared_ptr<MyClass> ptr1(new MyClass());
    {
        std::shared_ptr<MyClass> ptr2 = ptr1; // shared ownership
        // Both ptr1 and ptr2 point to the same MyClass object
    } // ptr2 goes out of scope, but the object is still alive
    // When ptr1 goes out of scope, the MyClass object is destroyed
    return 0;
}
```
**Choosing between `std::unique_ptr` and `std::shared_ptr`**
---------------------------------------------------------

* Use `std::unique_ptr` when:
	+ You need exclusive ownership of an object.
	+ You want to ensure that the object is deleted when the pointer goes out of scope.
* Use `std::shared_ptr` when:
	+ You need shared ownership of an object.
	+ You want to ensure that the object is deleted when the last pointer to it is destroyed.

Remember to prefer `std::unique_ptr` whenever possible, as it provides stronger guarantees about object lifetime and avoids the overhead of reference counting.

